data.content:
This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern — the classic case where `Thread.Abort` forcibly kills work that exceeds a deadline. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006).

## What's wrong on .NET 8

| .NET Framework API | .NET 8 behavior |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never triggered — dead code |

## Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // Task.Run moves the work to the thread pool — no manual Thread needed.
        var workTask = Task.Run(work);

        try
        {
            // WaitAsync throws TimeoutException if the task doesn't
            // complete within the deadline (.NET 6+ API).
            return workTask.WaitAsync(timeout).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (TimeoutException)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If the work is cancellation-aware (preferred)

When you control `work`, pass a `CancellationToken` so the work **actually stops** — not just gets abandoned:

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                       .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

Callers then cooperate:

```csharp
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return ComputeResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

## Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | The first version abandons the task but the thread keeps running. The `CancellationToken` version is the real fix. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` with a timeout creates an internal timer. Leaking it leaks the timer. Always `using`. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` ignores cancellation** | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` inside the work delegate. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Guard with `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Blocking on async code with `.Result`** | Can deadlock in UI/ASP.NET contexts with a `SynchronizationContext`. Prefer `async/await` end-to-end if possible. |

The `CancellationToken` version is strongly recommended — it's the only way to guarantee the work actually terminates.
